<div id="review_3403413429" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3403413429" />
    <a title="David Katzman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1444651-david-katzman"><img alt="David Katzman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1399048696p2/1444651.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3403413429?book_show_action=true">Aug 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Katzman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Katzman" href="/user/show/1444651-david-katzman">David Katzman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/53883121-posthumous-memoirs-of-br-s-cubas">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3403413429" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8017467617945927035">Fun and charming, the <i>Posthumous Memoirs of Brás Cubas</i> is a ground-breaking novel published in 1880 that feels in many ways like a precursor to more modern experimental stories. It’s witty like Oscar Wilde and digressive like Tristram Shandy. It’s an entertaining read with what I felt was a worthy theme running through it—the folly of all human desires.<br/><br/>And yet sometimes a small aspect of a book can leave a greater impact than the overall story itself. Amidst the clever asides and philosophical m</span>
  <span id="freeText8017467617945927035" style="display:none">Fun and charming, the <i>Posthumous Memoirs of Brás Cubas</i> is a ground-breaking novel published in 1880 that feels in many ways like a precursor to more modern experimental stories. It’s witty like Oscar Wilde and digressive like Tristram Shandy. It’s an entertaining read with what I felt was a worthy theme running through it—the folly of all human desires.<br /><br />And yet sometimes a small aspect of a book can leave a greater impact than the overall story itself. Amidst the clever asides and philosophical musings, it really shocked me each time the main character Brás Cubas would casually mention the African slaves in his household and that of the other mostly rich, mostly aristocratic characters. What was so disturbing about it is the realization of how clever intelligent individuals are so shaped by their cultural environment that they can be utterly blind to inhumanity. I think it can be important to read stories that flippantly include racism, as long as they are read critically. I think it’s actually good for us all to be reminded of how easy it is to slip into dehumanization of “the Other.” And how the legacy of slavery is not behind us but is obvious all around if you look and think critically. But even many intelligent people don’t question and challenge the status quo. People can be intelligent and yet still uncritical thinkers. These are different qualities. Then there are also the Machiavellian personalities that can see the inhumanity, but it’s just unimportant because it benefits them, or they have other priorities so it doesn’t matter. In this story, Brás Cubas is a rather selfish narcissistic person and slavery just doesn’t seem to register in his consciousness as something worth pondering. But it did make me ponder it, so in that regard the <i>Posthumous Memoirs of Brás Cubas</i> was a worthy shock to the system.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8017467617945927035" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


